metadata.name: 空-sora- #47
metadata.description:
Japanese word Sora(空) means Sky.

An abstract painting of a landscape with sky.
Drawing based on mathematics fractal.

Top has 3 variations.
Bottom has 4 variations.
Cloud has 3 variations.
Background has White or Black 2 variations.
Stroke has ON or OFF 2 variations.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
- Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
- Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 3200 x 4800 pixel (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Bauhaus art #Lovely colors #61
metadata.description:
My Lovely colors collection is in Bauhaus style
I have designed this collection in 6 layers
The first layer is the background
3 layers of design and combination of lines and shapes
The 5th layer of the cover and the last layer of the frame and noise

metadata.name: Snake Alley #196
metadata.description:
Snake Alley is a place in my neighborhood where the sidewalk is narrowly bounded by low-hanging branches on one side and a steep ditch one the other. I have seen countless snakes dart across the sidewalk there at dusk. 

I always wind up at Snake Alley, wearing sandals, at dusk.

This generative system creates unique outputs for each hash. The compositions are organized like spokes through a series of concentric rings, like the Dharmachakra, however these are twisted and centered around an out-spiraling function. Higher-torque versions look more twisted and gnarled, while low-torque versions look like rays emanating from the center.

A number of branches connect each outer ring with its adjacent, inner ring. The layers of branches fill the space with low, medium, or high density - full of circles drawn from the outer layers to the innermost layer. The circles themselves are small or large, within each output.

Fifteen color palettes named after different kinds of snakes were used to lightly color the edges, each drawn with equal likelihood. The titles and colors were adapted from different snake species, typically variants found in the southeastern US, when different colorations occur in other regions. The coral, corn, and milk snakes around Charleston have similar coloration in nature, and their similar color gradients reflect this fact.

I originally composed this artwork in the R Statistics language. I translated the system to p5.js for the one-year anniversary of fxhash. Proceeds from sales will go to Processing.org, the organization that is developing p5.js. #fxhashturnsone 

Verified NFT collectors can purchase a fine art print for their unique token at vadenart.com

About the artist: Kenny Vaden is a generative artist based in Charleston, SC. His art experience included drawing, painting, stained glass apprenticeships, and nature photography. Vaden’s code-based artworks are available online as limited edition or single edition fine art prints, as well as NFTs on Quantum.art, Flamingo DAO Flutter, OpenSea, Objkt, fxhash, and Foundation. More information about the artist and artwork is available on vadenart.com

metadata.name: fx(splash) #264
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.

metadata.name: Highly influential #21
metadata.description:
A few days ago i read an article in which it said that Leonardo da Vinci was a "scientist" and that he devised inventions that "changed the world".

At that moment i thought: "how would it be to make a generative art sketch of a machine invented by da Vinci?"

I don't know how well it turned out, but i hope you like it.

metadata.name: Sands of Time #48
metadata.description:
We've been recently inspired to do this work while being on vacation, in one the most vibrant cities in the world, in the hot pot and intermixture of cultures, terrains and soundscapes. Borrowing the metaphors of sand, from Negarestani's "Cyclonopedia", and of time from "Chronosis", these living substances, we wanted to represent some of the vibes, that have been implanted into our gritty enduring nomadic existence.

This work was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine
- #Tezos4Iran

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

November, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY
